<br>
How I rationalize it being balanced for mages to have root:<br>
<br>
Consider the cleric. The cleric was THE excellent force of both groups and raids. Raids needed clerics in twice the quantity of pretty much any other class. Most groups without a cleric were a joke compared to groups with a cleric. It's quite true that a clericless group could actually do better than one with a cleric, since clerics did not output damage. But how many pick up groups in OS did you see without a cleric? 2? Whatever the number there were a hell of a lot more groups with clerics than without.<br>
<br>
It was balanced by the fact that clerics were some of the worst solo xp in the game. Even with undead nukes, clerics just were not built to solo. Their best damage spells were worse mana/dmg ratio-wise than any other caster. They just couldn't solo.<br>
<br>
Now they can. The new changes allow them to solo quite well. But not only that. The new cleric changes, introduced to give groups reason to take a cle over druid, and and also to give clerics an alternative when they couldn't group at all. But really, these changes have increased cleric's versatility a LOT. They used to be pushed toward the end game more than any other class. Now they retain most of that shift, but also can keep up with a lot of classes solo.<br>
<br>
The balancing factor of clerixing sucking at solo was taken away. It's this point that I argue mages should have root or some type of defense.<br>
<br>
Mages have always been one of the most offensive classes in the game. The balancing factor was that we had no defense. We have gate. We have pets. We do not have fear, root, snare, slow, mez, charm, FD, DA, or whatever else you can think of. We have low hp and low ac. If we pull 2 mobs, we die or zone. If the mobs are weak we just kill them both, but it takes a crapload more mana, because we have to chain heal our pets as nuking would gain agro. If I get 2 mobs, I usually end up oom. It's always been justified before though, because of our offense.<br>
<br>
But just as cleric's raid healing hasn't gone anywhere, our offense hasn't gone anywhere. And where clerics had their drawback quashed, I don't see why ours can't be as well.<br>
<br>
Root, which out of any defensive spell would be my choice, is wielded by most casters. Wizards have it, necros have it, enchanters, druids, clerics, shaman all have it. Paladins, who are only half a caster, have it. Bards, Sks, Bls don't have it to my knowledge. But they're all hybrids, and SKs and esp. BLs are quite broken classes in several respects, so it's not worth discussing why they don't have root.<br>
<br>
Of all the casting classes, mages lack root. Why? Because we have the best offense of any of them? Clerics have the best pure defense, but it doesn't stop them from having quite a mean offense.<br>
<br>
One could easily say this argument about the clerics is irrelevent. Clerics were given these spells because druids and shaman threatened to move in on some of that defensive territory. <br>
<br>
But is our primary job on the uberest of uber encounters, and thus the pinnacle of mage hood, not making mod rods for clerics? With additional healing power coming from druids and shaman, I could counter the above counter-argument by saying that druid and shaman heals also cut into *our* roles, indirectly.<br>
<br>
The counter-counter-counter argument would be that I'm referring to the pinnacle of magehood, only the uberest of uber encounters, and that it once again makes my comparison to clerics irrelevant, since a good cleric will never use their new melee powers on anything which would pose such a challenge to their guild.<br>
<br>
So my counterx4 argument would then be that yeah, exactly, that's why I'm not asking for upgraded nukes or mod rods as compensation, but rather an ability which would be irrelevant on such encounters :p<br>
<br>
VI says they added the changes to balance clerics, not to throw them a bone because some other class got an upgrade. But let's face it, it was compensation for druid cheals. Either way you look at it, it's a good reason to have another look at mages getting root. Balance us, or compensate us~<br>
<br>
I've explored some reasons for mages getting root, along with toying with some counter-reasons, all of which were not without their counter-counters. So, anyone got any more anti-root arguments? I'm ready to hear them, this is the first time I've ever been on the pro-upgrade side of a class balance argument :Q <p><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=109465>~Krilen</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ukrilenspiritlink.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Krilen Spiritlink</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 311<br> <font color=#333333>(9/8/02 7:02:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=332.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> ==============<br>
