<br>
Magician = Conjuration/Summoner from D&amp;D<br>
Necromancer = Necromancer<br>
Enchanter = Illusionist/Diviner (these were two different specialized classes but EQ kinda combined them)<br>
Wizard = Invoker<br>
<br>
In D&amp;D there were serveral schools of magic and being a specialized caster meant you could not take part in certain schools because they conflicted with one another....<br>
<br>
This is where EQ screws up...<br>
<br>
In D&amp;D Conjuration/Summoners were bad ass. You didn't want to even think about facing one. They could summon multiple pets that could deal with serveral opponents. However they had no access to the Invocation/Evocation school of magic i.e....NO NUKES!!!!<br>
<br>
Invokers  were nasty. Magic Missle, Fire Bolt, Lighting Bolt. You name it they had it. DO NO F00K with a Invoker or you would get worked over. However they had no access to Conjuration/Summoning. The key is those two schools of magic are the most powerful offensively. So it wouldn't be ok for you to allow a class to specialize in one while having access to the other. In D&amp;D Invokers/Evokers (EQ's version of the wizard class) had no ability to summon a familiar. Familiars, pets, elementals, monters were all in the realm of the Conjurationist. <br>
<br>
Also in D&amp;D if I can remember correctly (it has been awhile) every class had some form of abjuration ability. Also in D&amp;D enchanters were not gimp offensively....Ummmm Phantasmal Killer anyone? =)<br>
<br>
Basically if EQ wanted to stick with the tradition of the caster. Then every casting class should get...<br>
<br>
Root<br>
Rune<br>
Damage Shield<br>
<br>
These three ability are present for any specialized caster in any roleplaying game. I do not understand why EQ insist on gimping mages so heavily in this area.  The funny part is necros/enchanters/Wizards all have....<br>
<br>
Root<br>
Rune<br>
Damage Shield <br>
<br>
