Root can be resisted as often as 1 of 4 times cast depending on the mob. A pet wont generaly instantly die when sent against a mob.<br>
<br>
Root get a new chance to break (same chance as initial resist) from every damage spell cast. A mob will stay on the pet as long as you do not nuke too fast.<br>
<br>
Somewhat obviously perhaps if you read the above, so will you get hit while using root most of the fights unless you have some way of outrunning mobs. Wizards are as good at that as magicians are. The only way for a wizard to use root without getting hit is to have som run speed boost. A magician could also use this to be able to cast a new pet without getting hit.<br>
<br>
Another side effect is that you will generaly have to use root several times each fight. At 30 to 100 mana for roots, so will this quickly add up to cost more then magician pets do.<br>
<br>
Pets also do some damage as a bonus, this extra damage is generaly much more then the small advantage wizards have in mana efficiency. This is very noticeable at lower levels making wizards more dependant on equipment then mages. It requires some decent int/mana to be able to kill 1 blue mob on a full mana bar.<br>
<br>
The dependancy on mana to do damage is also noticeable when handling adds. Every root on an add is that much less mana to use for killing the main target.<br>
<br>
Root will also work poorly on magic resistant mobs and not at all on mobs that are imune to root (not that uncommon). A mage can switch to fire based damage, healing pet or chain casting pets to get around that.<br>
